Interesting article/interview on Salon today about Ray Bradbury, and in particular his book Fahrenheit 451.  I read the book back in the 80s while in high school and remember at the time dismissing it as another Orwellian view of the future that would never happen.  Turns out I was wrong.<br>
<br>
The book, in case you haven't read it or seen the 1966 film adaptation, is about a future where books are completely banned by the government.   Firemen no longer put out fires, but instead carry kerosene flamethrowers to ignite censored books.   <br>
<br>
&quot;Kerosene-spraying firemen aside, a closer look at the 1953 novel shows Bradbury nailed the new millennium perfectly. There's interactive television, stereo earphones (which reportedly inspired a Sony engineer to invent the Walkman), immersive wall-size TVs, earpiece communicators, rampant political correctness, omnipresent advertising and a violent youth culture ignored by self-absorbed, prescription-dependent parents.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;In the novel, Fire Captain Beatty explains to Montag, the conflicted fireman, that their government didn't ban reading. Books were simply marginalized as an increasingly inoffensive media and a growing population embraced infotainment at the expense of &quot;slippery stuff like philosophy or sociology.&quot; <br>
<br>
